=== ROUTE PROTECTION AUDIT ===

CONTRADICTION: Previous summary claimed "proxy.ts provides auth guards."
REALITY: proxy.ts exists at root but is NOT middleware.ts. Next.js ignores it.
  - No root middleware.ts exists (required at / or /src/ for Next.js middleware)
  - proxy.ts exports a `proxy()` function, not `middleware()`
  - Zero files import proxy.ts — it is dead code
  - The build output "ƒ Proxy (Middleware)" refers to Next.js internal dynamic route handling, not this file

FINDINGS:
1. NO Next.js middleware exists — zero request-level auth interception
2. Admin layout (app/admin/layout.tsx) uses server-side `requireAdmin()` — GOOD
3. LMS layout (app/lms/(app)/layout.tsx) uses CLIENT-SIDE auth check — WEAK (can be bypassed by direct API calls)
4. Instructor layout (app/instructor/layout.tsx) uses server-side auth check — GOOD
5. Staff portal — no layout.tsx found — NO PROTECTION
6. API routes: 917 total, ~469 lack explicit auth references
7. Admin API routes: 2 confirmed completely unprotected:
   - app/api/admin/applications/[id]/approve/route.ts — uses supabaseAdmin with ZERO auth, can create users
   - app/api/admin/send-reminder/route.ts — uses createAdminClient with ZERO auth, can trigger SMS
8. ~198 non-admin API routes lack any auth reference (some may be intentionally public)

SEVERITY: HIGH — No middleware means all route protection depends on individual layout/route handler checks.
Any route that forgets to check auth is publicly accessible.

=== CORRECTION (post-build verification) ===
proxy.ts IS active in Next.js 16 (replaces middleware.ts).
Build output "ƒ Proxy (Middleware)" confirms this.
However, proxy.ts explicitly skips /api/* routes (line ~210):
  if (pathname.startsWith('/api/')) { return NextResponse.next(); }
This means API routes have zero proxy-level protection.
Page routes ARE protected by proxy.ts auth checks.
